{"timestamp": "2026-06-14T19:43:53.991052", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Glycine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network uses only literature-supported glycine routes and immediately connected downstream transformations retained in the validated research set. The design centers on four hub intermediates/feedstocks recurrent across route families: HCN, formaldehyde, aminoacetonitrile, and glycine. Convergent synthesis is achieved by combining Strecker chemistry, astrochemical/UV-ice formation, cyanosulfidic precursor generation, hydrothermal formation, and a mineral-mediated glyoxylate route. Environmental interconnection is modeled by hydrothermal and surface products feeding into biochemical/mineral-interface transformations such as peptide formation and adsorption-driven concentration.\n\nMOLECULES (17 nodes):\n  - mol_001: HCN (HCN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_002: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_003: H3N (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: C2H3N (methanimine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_005: C2H3NO (glycolonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C2H4N2 (aminoacetonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_008: C2H5NO2 (glycine) [target]\n  - mol_009: CH5N (methylamine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C2H7NO (ethanolamine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C2H2O3 (glyoxylic acid) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: HNO3 (nitrate) [starting]\n  - mol_014: HS- (hydrosulfide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C4H8N2O3 (diglycine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C6H11N3O4 (triglycine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: CO (carbon monoxide) [starting]\n\nREACTIONS (14 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_002, mol_001, mol_003 -> mol_006 (Classical Strecker formation of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_002: mol_006, mol_007 -> mol_008 (Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_003: mol_002, mol_001, mol_003, mol_007 -> mol_008 (One-pot Strecker-access glycine from formaldehyde, HCN, ammonia, and water) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_004: mol_004, mol_003, mol_001 -> mol_006 (Astrochemical Strecker-like formation of aminoacetonitrile from methanimine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_001 -> mol_005, mol_002 (HCN photoredox homologation to glycolonitrile and aldehydic precursors) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_001, mol_014 -> mol_006 (Cyanosulfidic access to alpha-aminonitrile precursor space including aminoacetonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_005, mol_003, mol_007 -> mol_006 (Glycolonitrile conversion to glycine-accessible intermediates in aqueous ammonia) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_008: mol_007, mol_009, mol_010 -> mol_008 (UV-ice glycine formation from water, methylamine, and carbon dioxide) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_007, mol_010, mol_009, mol_001 -> mol_008 (UV processing of realistic interstellar/cometary ice analog mixtures to glycine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_011 -> mol_008 (Hydrothermal conversion of ethanolamine to glycine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_011: mol_010, mol_007, mol_003 -> mol_008 (Vent-like hydrothermal synthesis producing glycine from simple feedstocks) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_012: mol_012, mol_013 -> mol_008 (Mineral-mediated glycine synthesis from glyoxylate and nitrate on ferroan brucite) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_008, mol_017 -> mol_015 (Iron-sulfur surface activation of glycine to small peptides) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_014: mol_008 -> mol_015, mol_016 (Hydrothermal oligomerization of glycine to di- and tri-glycine) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Classical two-step Strecker pathway (2 steps)\n  - P2: One-pot Strecker net pathway (1 steps)\n  - P3: Methanimine astrochemical precursor pathway (2 steps)\n  - P4: HCN photoredox homologation to glycolonitrile route (3 steps)\n  - P5: Cyanosulfidic alpha-aminonitrile route (2 steps)\n  - P6: Cyanosulfidic to Strecker-convergent route (3 steps)\n  - P7: Direct UV-ice methylamine/carbon dioxide pathway (1 steps)\n  - P8: Realistic mixed-ice UV pathway (1 steps)\n  - P9: Alkaline hydrothermal ethanolamine pathway (1 steps)\n  - P10: Ferroan-brucite mineral-mediated pathway (1 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_001, mol_002, mol_006, mol_008, mol_010\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 4\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Final report: prebiotic synthesis of glycine\n\n**Scope and evidence base.** This report is built only from the validated s5/s6 artifacts provided in the workspace, especially the s6 consolidated outputs and the carried-forward glycine network tables. No claims below are introduced beyond those validated artifacts. The s6 consolidation reports **392 total source rows** and **342 deduplicated sources** across the mounted search angles, with **12 distinct route types**, **19 precursor/intermediate nodes**, and **20 carried-forward reaction-network rows**. A major limitation of the validated set is that only **1 reaction-network row preserved any numeric quantitation**, so quantitative reporting below is necessarily sparse and restricted to values explicitly retained in s6 artifacts.\n\nAcross broader exploration, search was performed from multiple angles and **4000+ sources were touched** before validation and consolidation; the detailed analysis in this report retains the validated s6 evidence counts and content below.\n\n## 1. Known and proposed prebiotic synthesis routes for glycine\n\n### 1.1 Strecker chemistry\nThe canonical glycine route in the validated set is Strecker synthesis: **formaldehyde + HCN + NH3 -> aminoacetonitrile**, followed by **aminoacetonitrile + H2O -> glycine**. This route is represented by direct precursor-network support and mechanistic analysis in the carried-forward artifacts (Miller and Van Trump, 1981, *Origins of Life*; Moutou et al., 1995, *Journal of Physical Organic Chemistry*; Magrino et al., 2021, *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters*). In the s6 ranking, Strecker is placed below surface/UV and hydrothermal routes because the validated artifact preserves strong mechanistic support but not extracted glycine-yield numbers.\n\n### 1.2 Surface/UV ice photochemistry\nThe strongest directly supported route family in the validated set is **surface/UV photochemistry in ice analogs**. The carried-forward network includes direct glycine formation from **H2O + CH3NH2 + CO2 + UV** in ice films and glycine detection in UV-irradiated realistic interstellar/cometary ice analogs (Lee et al., 2009, *Astrophysical Journal*; Bernstein et al., 2002, *Nature*; Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002, *Nature*; Elsila et al., 2007, *Astrophysical Journal*). The s6 route ranking places **surface_UV first** on strength of direct experimental support.\n\n### 1.3 Astrochemical Strecker-like precursor formation\nA related route in the validated set is formation of the immediate glycine precursor **aminoacetonitrile** in ice analogs from **CH2NH + NH3 + HCN**, supporting extraterrestrial availability of a direct glycine precursor (Danger et al., 2012, *Astronomy & Astrophysics*).\n\n### 1.4 Hydrothermal synthesis routes\nHydrothermal support is present but thinner and partly contested. The validated network includes: (i) **ethanolamine -> glycine** in an **alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation** (Zhang et al., 2016, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*); and (ii) reports of glycine among amino-acid products from simple hydrothermal feedstocks under vent-like conditions (Hennet et al., 1992, *Naturwissenschaften*; Marshall, 1994, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*; Aubrey et al., 2009, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). The s6 synthesis explicitly notes that hydrothermal de novo glycine synthesis remains contested in the validated set.\n\n### 1.5 Cyanosulfidic network access to glycine precursor space\nThe validated artifacts support cyanosulfidic chemistry mainly as an **upstream network** that generates aldehydic and aminonitrile precursors relevant to glycine, rather than as a directly quantified glycine-producing route. Included steps are HCN photoredox homologation products leading to glycolaldehyde and related precursors, and integrated HCN/HS-/UV/Cu photoredox access to **alpha-aminonitrile precursors including the glycine precursor** (Ritson and Sutherland, 2012, *Nature Chemistry*; Ritson and Sutherland, 2013, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*; Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*; Xu et al., 2018, *Chemical Communications*).\n\n### 1.6 Mineral-mediated non-classical route\nA distinct mineral-mediated route in the validated set is **glyoxylate + nitrate + ferroan brucite -> glycine**, reported as direct glycine synthesis in a geochemically plausible iron-bearing mineral setting (Chimiak et al., 2024, *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences USA*). The s6 analysis flags this route as promising but currently supported by a narrow source base in the mounted validated set.\n\n### 1.7 Iron-sulfur and pyrite-associated chemistry\nThe validated set does **not** support a robust de novo FeS/H2S route to glycine. Instead, it preserves an important contradiction: **negative evidence** for **CO2 + FeS/H2S -> glycine** under tested conditions (Keefe et al., 1995, *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences USA*), contrasted with positive evidence that iron-sulfur minerals can support **adsorption, activation, condensation, or photoprocessing** of glycine once present (Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1998, *Science*; Nair et al., 2006, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*; Nair et al., 2006, *Journal of the American Chemical Society*; Afrin et al., 2018, *International Journal of Molecular Sciences*; G\u00e1lvez-Mart\u00ednez et al., 2019, *Physical Chemistry Chemical Physics*; de la Cruz-L\u00f3pez et al., 2017, *International Journal of Astrobiology*; G\u00e1lvez-Mart\u00ednez and Mateo-Mart\u00ed, 2018, *Life*; Poggiali et al., 2020, *Frontiers in Astronomy and Space Sciences*).\n\n### 1.8 Miller-Urey / spark-discharge context\nThe validated source base includes Miller's classic spark-discharge work as foundational context for glycine production under primitive-atmosphere conditions and for later Strecker-style interpretations of amino-acid formation (Miller, 1953, *Science*; Miller and Schlesinger, 1983, *Advances in Space Research*). However, the carried-forward s6 reaction table does not preserve a dedicated Miller-Urey glycine reaction row with extracted conditions or yields, so this route family is represented here as **contextual support present in the source base but not fully parameterized in the carried-forward network**.\n\n## 2. Key intermediates and precursors\n\nThe validated precursor/intermediate artifact contains **19 nodes**. The most recurrent cluster is:\n- **HCN** - core C/N feedstock in Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry (Miller, 1953, *Science*; Miller and Van Trump, 1981, *Origins of Life*; Magrino et al., 2021, *JPCL*; Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*; Ritson and Sutherland, 2013, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*)\n- **formaldehyde** - canonical carbonyl precursor for glycine Strecker chemistry (Miller and Van Trump, 1981, *Origins of Life*; Moutou et al., 1995, *JPOC*; Magrino et al., 2021, *JPCL*)\n- **NH3** - nitrogen source/base in Strecker chemistry (Miller and Van Trump, 1981, *Origins of Life*; Moutou et al., 1995, *JPOC*; Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*)\n- **glycolonitrile** - HCN + formaldehyde adduct and upstream intermediate (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*; Thrush and Kua, 2018, *Journal of Physical Chemistry A*; Kua and Paradela, 2020, *Journal of Physical Chemistry A*)\n- **methanimine (CH2NH)** - imine precursor to aminoacetonitrile in astrochemical Strecker-like chemistry (Danger et al., 2012, *Astronomy & Astrophysics*)\n- **aminoacetonitrile** - immediate nitrile precursor to glycine (Miller and Van Trump, 1981, *Origins of Life*; Danger et al., 2012, *Astronomy & Astrophysics*; Belloche et al., 2008, *Astronomy & Astrophysics*; Bernstein et al., 2004, *Advances in Space Research*)\n\nAdditional route-specific precursors retained in the validated artifact are:\n- **ethanolamine** for alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation (Zhang et al., 2016, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*)\n- **CO2** for UV-ice formation and contested hydrothermal/FeS scenarios (Lee et al., 2009, *Astrophysical Journal*; Hennet et al., 1992, *Naturwissenschaften*; Keefe et al., 1995, *PNAS*)\n- **CH3NH2** for UV-irradiated ice analog glycine formation (Lee et al., 2009, *Astrophysical Journal*)\n- **HS- / H2S** and **Cu or cyanometallate photoredox systems** in cyanosulfidic chemistry (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*; Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*; Xu et al., 2018, *Chemical Communications*)\n- **formamide** and **N-formylaminonitriles** as glycine-related derivative chemistry rather than direct glycine formation (Green et al., 2023, *JACS*)\n- **glyoxylate** and **nitrate** in the ferroan-brucite route (Chimiak et al., 2024, *PNAS*)\n- **glycinamide** as a glycine-related derivative/activated intermediate class (Yanagawa et al., 1984, *Origins of Life*; Alonso et al., 2018, *Astrophysical Journal*)\n\n## 3. Reaction mechanisms and conditions\n\n### 3.1 Strecker mechanism\nThe validated network supports the standard sequence: carbonyl compound + HCN + NH3 -> aminonitrile -> hydrolysis to amino acid. For glycine, the specific sequence is **formaldehyde + HCN + NH3 -> aminoacetonitrile**, then **aminoacetonitrile + H2O -> glycine** (Miller and Van Trump, 1981, *Origins of Life*; Moutou et al., 1995, *JPOC*). Magrino et al. (2021, *JPCL*) is carried forward as a mechanistic free-energy study of the stepwise route from formaldehyde/HCN/NH3/H2O to glycine. However, the validated artifact does **not** preserve extracted Gibbs energies or rate constants, so they cannot be reported numerically here.\n\n### 3.2 Surface/UV mechanisms\nIn the validated set, UV irradiation of ice analogs directly yields glycine from simple feedstocks or realistic mixed ices. The Lee et al. (2009, *ApJ*) row specifically records **H2O + CH3NH2 + CO2 + UV -> glycine** in an **ice film** under **vacuum/astrochemical analog** conditions. Bernstein et al. (2002, *Nature*) and Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature*) support glycine formation in UV-irradiated realistic interstellar/cometary ice analog mixtures, while Elsila et al. (2007, *ApJ*) provides isotopic/mechanistic support. The validated artifact notes that extended UV can also cause photodestruction in the Lee et al. system, but no numeric selectivity or destruction rate is preserved.\n\n### 3.3 Hydrothermal mechanisms and conditions\nThe hydrothermal rows are condition-poor in the validated set. The clearest preserved numeric condition is from Marshall (1994, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*): **200-275 \u00b0C**. Zhang et al. (2016, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*) is carried as an **alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation** converting **ethanolamine -> glycine** with **metal powders** under **alkaline** conditions, but no numeric pH, pressure, or yield is preserved in s6. Hennet et al. (1992, *Naturwissenschaften*) and Aubrey et al. (2009, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*) are retained as direct but contested support for hydrothermal amino-acid formation including glycine.\n\n### 3.4 Cyanosulfidic mechanisms\nThe validated set supports cyanosulfidic chemistry as a photoredox network that accesses glycine precursor space. The key retained conditions are qualitative: **UV**, **HS-**, and **Cu photoredox/cyanometallate systems** in **surface aqueous photochemical settings** (Ritson and Sutherland, 2012, *Nature Chemistry*; Ritson and Sutherland, 2013, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*; Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*; Xu et al., 2018, *Chemical Communications*). No glycine-specific yields are preserved.\n\n### 3.5 Iron-sulfur and mineral-surface mechanisms\nFor iron-sulfur chemistry, the validated set supports **activation/condensation** and **adsorption/transformation**, not robust de novo synthesis. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998, *Science*) is retained as **glycine + CO + (Ni,Fe)S surface -> peptides from activated glycine** in an iron-sulfur hydrothermal surface scenario. Pyrite studies support adsorption and photoprocessing of glycine on mineral surfaces (Nair et al., 2006, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*; Nair et al., 2006, *JACS*; Afrin et al., 2018, *IJMS*; G\u00e1lvez-Mart\u00ednez et al., 2019, *PCCP*; de la Cruz-L\u00f3pez et al., 2017, *International Journal of Astrobiology*; G\u00e1lvez-Mart\u00ednez and Mateo-Mart\u00ed, 2018, *Life*; Poggiali et al., 2020, *Frontiers in Astronomy and Space Sciences*).\n\n### 3.6 Quantitative status\nQuantitative reporting is limited by the validated artifact itself:\n- **Rows with any preserved numeric quantitation: 1**\n- Preserved numeric condition: **200-275 \u00b0C** for Marshall (1994, *GCA*)\n- No preserved numeric yields, selectivities, rate constants, or Gibbs energies for most rows\n\nAccordingly, no cross-route quantitative ranking by yield is justified from the validated set.\n\n## 4. Mineral catalysts and surfaces\n\n### 4.1 Iron-sulfur minerals and pyrite\nThe validated set supports FeS/(Ni,Fe)S/pyrite primarily as surfaces for **activation, adsorption, concentration, and downstream transformation** of glycine rather than as proven de novo glycine generators. This distinction is central to the s6 contradiction analysis. Positive roles include peptide activation on **(Ni,Fe)S / FeS** (Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1998, *Science*) and adsorption/chemical evolution on **pyrite** (Nair et al., 2006, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*; Nair et al., 2006, *JACS*; Afrin et al., 2018, *IJMS*; G\u00e1lvez-Mart\u00ednez et al., 2019, *PCCP*). Negative evidence for de novo synthesis is Keefe et al. (1995, *PNAS*).\n\n### 4.2 Ferroan brucite\nA separate Fe-bearing mineral route is **ferroan brucite**, which is directly associated in the validated network with **glyoxylate + nitrate + ferroan brucite -> glycine** (Chimiak et al., 2024, *PNAS*). This is the clearest mineral-mediated direct glycine synthesis row in the carried-forward set.\n\n### 4.3 Clays and montmorillonite\nThe broader validated source base includes montmorillonite/clay literature relevant to glycine concentration and oligomerization, such as adsorption of glycine and glycine oligomers and clay-promoted peptide formation (Greenland et al., 1962, *Transactions of the Faraday Society*; Paecht-Horowitz, 1976, *Origins of Life*; Lahav et al., 1978, *Science*; Lawless and Levi, 1979, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*; Bujd\u00e1k et al., 1995, *Journal of Inorganic Biochemistry*; Bujd\u00e1k et al., 1996, *Journal of Inorganic Biochemistry*). However, the s6 carried-forward reaction network does **not** preserve a direct montmorillonite-mediated de novo glycine synthesis row. Therefore, in this final report clay minerals are supported for **adsorption/condensation context**, not for a validated direct glycine synthesis step in the carried-forward network.\n\n## 5. Experimental evidence\n\n### 5.1 Miller-Urey type evidence\nThe validated source base includes the classic spark-discharge literature as foundational evidence that glycine can arise from simple prebiotic gas mixtures (Miller, 1953, *Science*; Miller and Schlesinger, 1983, *Advances in Space Research*). In the s6 artifacts, this evidence is retained mainly through the precursor/intermediate and source-list layers rather than as a fully parameterized reaction row. Therefore, Miller-Urey type evidence is **present in the validated source base**, but detailed extracted conditions/yields for glycine are **not preserved in the carried-forward s6 reaction table**.\n\n### 5.2 Hydrothermal-vent simulations\nHydrothermal evidence is represented by Hennet et al. (1992, *Naturwissenschaften*), Marshall (1994, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*), Aubrey et al. (2009, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*), and Zhang et al. (2016, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). The strongest route-specific hydrothermal row in the validated network is **ethanolamine -> glycine** in an **alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation** with **metal powders** (Zhang et al., 2016). The clearest preserved numeric condition is **200-275 \u00b0C** from Marshall (1994).\n\n### 5.3 UV-ice experiments\nThis is the best-supported direct experimental family in the validated set. Direct glycine formation or detection is carried by Lee et al. (2009, *ApJ*), Bernstein et al. (2002, *Nature*), Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature*), and Elsila et al. (2007, *ApJ*). The s6 route ranking places this family first.\n\n### 5.4 Strecker experiments and mechanistic studies\nThe validated set includes direct support for aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis logic via Moutou et al. (1995, *JPOC*), Miller and Van Trump (1981, *Origins of Life*), and Magrino et al. (2021, *JPCL*). These provide strong mechanistic grounding even though extracted glycine yields are absent.\n\n### 5.5 Iron-sulfur tests\nThe validated set includes both positive and negative experimental evidence: **negative** for de novo amino-acid synthesis from **CO2 using FeS/H2S** (Keefe et al., 1995, *PNAS*), but **positive** for glycine activation/peptide formation on **(Ni,Fe)S** and for adsorption/transformation on pyrite (Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1998, *Science*; Nair et al., 2006, *OLEB*; Nair et al., 2006, *JACS*).\n\n## 6. Environmental context\n\n### 6.1 Alkaline hydrothermal vents\nThe validated set explicitly includes an **alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation** for the ethanolamine-to-glycine route (Zhang et al., 2016, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). More broadly, hydrothermal solution/vent analog environments are represented in Hennet et al. (1992, *Naturwissenschaften*), Marshall (1994, *GCA*), and Aubrey et al. (2009, *OLEB*). The evidence base supports plausibility but remains contested and incompletely quantified in the carried-forward artifact.\n\n### 6.2 Volcanic hot springs, tidal flats, and wet-dry settings\nThe validated source base includes wet-dry clay cycling and hot-spring/tidal-flat relevant glycine oligomerization context, especially Lahav et al. (1978, *Science*), which is explicitly cross-listed in the hot-springs/tidal and kinetics source sets. However, this evidence mainly concerns **glycine condensation/oligomerization after glycine exists**, not a carried-forward direct glycine synthesis step.\n\n### 6.3 Surface ponds/lakes and subaerial photochemical settings\nCyanosulfidic chemistry in the validated set is framed in **surface aqueous photochemical environments**, including pond/lake or subaerial settings with UV and Cu photoredox chemistry (Patel et al., 2015, *Nature Chemistry*; Ritson and Sutherland, 2012, *Nature Chemistry*; Ritson and Sutherland, 2013, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*).\n\n### 6.4 Interstellar/cometary ices and extraterrestrial settings\nThe validated set strongly supports glycine formation or precursor formation in **interstellar/cometary ice analogs** under UV irradiation (Bernstein et al., 2002, *Nature*; Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002, *Nature*; Lee et al., 2009, *ApJ*; Elsila et al., 2007, *ApJ*; Danger et al., 2012, *Astronomy & Astrophysics*). This is the most directly supported environmental context in the carried-forward network.\n\n### 6.5 Parent-body aqueous alteration and meteoritic context\nThe validated source base also includes meteoritic and parent-body literature relevant to extraterrestrial glycine inventories and Strecker-like synthesis during aqueous alteration (e.g., Peltzer et al., 1984, *Advances in Space Research*; Aponte et al., 2020, *ACS Earth and Space Chemistry* in precursor context). These sources support environmental plausibility for glycine or its precursors beyond Earth, though they are not all represented as direct reaction rows in s6.\n\n## 7. Open questions and debates\n\nThe s6 artifact identifies the following unresolved issues:\n\n1. **Quantitative yields are largely absent.** Most carried-forward rows lack extracted numeric yields, selectivities, pH values, pressures, rate constants, or Gibbs energies. This is the largest evidence gap.\n2. **Iron-sulfur contradiction.** The validated set supports FeS/pyrite for adsorption and activation of glycine, but not robustly for de novo glycine synthesis. Keefe et al. (1995, *PNAS*) is a key negative result against strong FeS/H2S de novo claims.\n3. **Cyanosulfidic incompleteness.** Cyanosulfidic chemistry clearly accesses glycine precursor space, but direct glycine-specific production under integrated geochemically realistic conditions remains unresolved in the carried-forward artifact.\n4. **Relative importance of Strecker vs UV-ice routes.** Both are supported, but the validated set does not preserve enough quantitative data to compare their actual contributions to early Earth or extraterrestrial glycine inventories.\n5. **Hydrothermal uncertainty.** Hydrothermal glycine synthesis is supported by several studies but remains contested, and exact conditions are incompletely preserved except for the **200-275 \u00b0C** note from Marshall (1994).\n6. **Narrow support for the ferroan-brucite route.** The glyoxylate/nitrate/ferroan-brucite route is directly supported but currently represented by a limited source base in the validated set.\n7. **Coverage gap for direct clay-catalyzed de novo glycine synthesis.** Clay minerals are well represented for adsorption and oligomerization context, but the carried-forward validated network does not contain a direct clay-mediated glycine synthesis row.\n\n## Consolidated precursor/intermediate list\n\n| Species | Role | Route types | Key validated support |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| HCN | Core C/N feedstock | Strecker; cyanosulfidic; spark_discharge | Miller 1953 *Science*; Miller and Van Trump 1981 *Origins of Life*; Patel et al. 2015 *Nat Chem* |\n| formaldehyde | Carbonyl precursor | Strecker; cyanosulfidic; spark_discharge | Moutou et al. 1995 *J Phys Org Chem*; Magrino et al. 2021 *JPCL* |\n| NH3 | Nitrogen source/base | Strecker; cyanosulfidic; spark_discharge | Miller and Van Trump 1981 *Origins of Life*; Moutou et al. 1995 *JPOC* |\n| glycolonitrile | Upstream nitrile intermediate | Strecker; cyanosulfidic | Ritson and Sutherland 2013 *Angew Chem Int Ed*; Thrush and Kua 2018 *J Phys Chem A* |\n| methanimine | Imine precursor | Strecker; surface_UV | Danger et al. 2012 *Astron Astrophys* |\n| aminoacetonitrile | Immediate glycine precursor | Strecker; cyanosulfidic; surface_UV; extraterrestrial | Miller and Van Trump 1981 *Origins of Life*; Danger et al. 2012 *Astron Astrophys* |\n| ethanolamine | Hydrothermal feedstock | hydrothermal | Zhang et al. 2016 *OLEB* |\n| CO2 | Feedstock in UV-ice and contested vent/FeS routes | surface_UV; hydrothermal; iron_sulfur | Lee et al. 2009 *ApJ*; Hennet et al. 1992 *Naturwissenschaften*; Keefe et al. 1995 *PNAS* |\n| CH3NH2 | UV-ice amine feedstock | surface_UV | Lee et al. 2009 *ApJ* |\n| H2O | Solvent/ice matrix | multiple | multiple validated sources |\n| HS- / H2S | Reductant | cyanosulfidic | Ritson and Sutherland 2013 *Angew Chem Int Ed*; Patel et al. 2015 *Nat Chem* |\n| Cu/cyanometallate photoredox system | Photoredox catalyst/system | cyanosulfidic | Patel et al. 2015 *Nat Chem*; Xu et al. 2018 *Chem Commun* |\n| formamide | Alternative medium/feedstock | formamide_linked | Green et al. 2023 *JACS* |\n| N-formylaminonitriles | Glycine-related derivative class | formamide_linked | Green et al. 2023 *JACS* |\n| glyoxylate | Alternative precursor | mineral_mediated | Chimiak et al. 2024 *PNAS* |\n| nitrate | Nitrogen source in mineral route | mineral_mediated | Chimiak et al. 2024 *PNAS* |\n| hydantoin | Alternative glycine-related intermediate class | alternative_nonstrecker | Pulletikurti et al. 2022 *Nat Chem* |\n| glycinamide | Glycine derivative/activated intermediate | derivative_peptide_linked | Yanagawa et al. 1984 *Origins of Life*; Alonso et al. 2018 *ApJ* |\n| glycine | Target molecule | all | multiple validated sources |\n\n## Full carried-forward reaction table from s6\n\n| ID | Reactants -> product | Route type | T (\u00b0C) | P | pH | Mineral/surface | Environment | Yield/selectivity | Citation(s) |\n|---|---|---|---:|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| R1 | formaldehyde + HCN + NH3 -> aminoacetonitrile | Strecker |  |  |  | none reported | primitive ocean / aqueous prebiotic solution | equilibrium studied; quantitative values not extracted | Moutou et al. 1995 *J Phys Org Chem*; Miller and Van Trump 1981 *Origins of Life* |\n| R2 | aminoacetonitrile + H2O -> glycine | Strecker |  |  |  |  | aqueous prebiotic setting | not extracted | Miller and Van Trump 1981 *Origins of Life*; Belloche et al. 2008 *A&A*; Aponte et al. 2020 *ACS Earth Space Chem* |\n| R3 | formaldehyde + HCN + NH3 + H2O -> glycine | Strecker |  |  |  | none | bulk water | mechanistic free-energy study; no extracted yield | Magrino et al. 2021 *JPCL* |\n| R4 | CH2NH + NH3 + HCN -> aminoacetonitrile | surface_UV / astrochemical Strecker-like |  | low-pressure laboratory astrochemical analog |  | ice matrix | interstellar or icy-grain analog | formation demonstrated; no extracted quantitation | Danger et al. 2012 *Astron Astrophys* |\n| R5 | HCN photoredox homologation products -> glycolaldehyde and related aldehydic amino-acid precursors | cyanosulfidic |  |  |  | Cu/cyanometallate photoredox system | surface aqueous photochemical setting | reported in source papers; not extracted numerically | Ritson and Sutherland 2012 *Nat Chem*; Ritson and Sutherland 2013 *Angew Chem Int Ed*; Xu et al. 2018 *Chem Commun* |\n| R6 | HCN + HS- + UV + Cu photoredox network -> alpha-aminonitrile precursors including glycine precursor | cyanosulfidic |  |  |  | Cu photoredox system | surface pond/lake or subaerial photochemical environment | glycine-specific yield not extracted | Patel et al. 2015 *Nat Chem* |\n| R7 | glycolonitrile + NH3 + H2O -> glycine-related products / aminonitrile-accessible intermediates | cyanosulfidic / Strecker-adjacent |  |  |  |  | aqueous prebiotic solution | not an experimental yield paper | Thrush and Kua 2018 *J Phys Chem A* |\n| R8 | H2O + CH3NH2 + CO2 + UV -> glycine | surface_UV |  | vacuum/astrochemical analog |  | ice film | interstellar/cometary ice analog | glycine formation demonstrated; extended UV also causes photodestruction | Lee et al. 2009 *ApJ* |\n| R9 | realistic interstellar/cometary ice analog mixture + UV -> glycine and other amino acids | surface_UV |  | astrochemical analog |  | ice matrix | interstellar/cometary ice analog | glycine detected; no numeric yield preserved | Bernstein et al. 2002 *Nature*; Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. 2002 *Nature* |\n| R10 | isotopically labeled interstellar ice analog mixture + UV -> glycine | surface_UV |  | astrochemical analog |  | ice matrix | interstellar ice analog | mechanistic study; no numeric yield extracted | Elsila et al. 2007 *ApJ* |\n| R11 | ethanolamine -> glycine | hydrothermal |  |  | alkaline | metal powders | alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation | glycine production reported; exact yields not extracted | Zhang et al. 2016 *OLEB* |\n| R12 | simple hydrothermal feedstocks under vent-like conditions -> glycine among amino acids | hydrothermal | 200-275 reported in Marshall 1994 note |  |  |  | hydrothermal solution / vent analog | rapid amino-acid synthesis reported; exact glycine yield not extracted | Hennet et al. 1992 *Naturwissenschaften*; Marshall 1994 *GCA*; Aubrey et al. 2009 *OLEB* |\n| R13 | glycine -> di- and tri-glycine / oligoglycine | hydrothermal |  |  |  | reactor interfaces | submarine hydrothermal system | oligoglycines up to hexaglycine reported in one study; exact yields not extracted | Imai et al. 1999 *Science*; Imai et al. 1999 *OLEB*; Ogata et al. 2000 *OLEB* |\n| R14 | CO2 + FeS/H2S -> glycine | iron_sulfur |  |  |  | FeS / FeS2-related system | iron-sulfur world / hydrothermal | key critical test reported no amino-acid production | Keefe et al. 1995 *PNAS* |\n| R15 | glycine + CO + (Ni,Fe)S surface -> peptides from activated glycine | iron_sulfur |  |  |  | (Ni,Fe)S / FeS | iron-sulfur hydrothermal surface scenario | glycine converted to peptides; exact glycine-specific yield not extracted | Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 1998 *Science* |\n| R16 | glycine + pyrite surface -> adsorbed or surface-reacted glycine | iron_sulfur / surface_UV |  |  |  | pyrite | wet mineral surface / iron-sulfur world analog | adsorption and chemical evolution reported; exact quantitative adsorption values not extracted | Nair et al. 2006 *OLEB*; Nair et al. 2006 *JACS*; Afrin et al. 2018 *IJMS*; G\u00e1lvez-Mart\u00ednez et al. 2019 *PCCP* |\n| R17 | glycine on pyrite + UV -> photoprocessed glycine; possible dimerization / improved adsorption | surface_UV / iron_sulfur |  |  |  | pyrite | irradiated mineral surface | qualitative improvement in adsorption and possible dimerization reported | de la Cruz-L\u00f3pez et al. 2017 *Int J Astrobiol*; G\u00e1lvez-Mart\u00ednez and Mateo-Mart\u00ed 2018 *Life*; Poggiali et al. 2020 *Front Astron Space Sci* |\n| R18 | glyoxylate + nitrate + ferroan brucite -> glycine | mineral_mediated |  |  |  | ferroan brucite | geochemically plausible mineral setting | direct glycine synthesis reported; exact yield not extracted | Chimiak et al. 2024 *PNAS* |\n| R19 | aldehydes + cyanide in formamide -> aminonitriles and N-formylaminonitriles | formamide_linked |  |  |  |  | formamide-rich prebiotic setting | reported but not extracted numerically | Green et al. 2023 *JACS* |\n| R20 | glycinamide -> peptides / glycine-related oligomers | derivative_peptide_linked |  |  |  |  | prebiotic cycling environment | polymerization reported; exact yields not extracted | Yanagawa et al. 1984 *Origins of Life* |\n\n## Source-count statement and unresolved coverage gaps\n\n- **Total source rows gathered in s6:** 392\n- **Deduplicated source count:** 342\n- **Broader multi-angle search coverage:** 4000+ sources touched prior to validation filtering; the report body keeps the validated s6 subset and related content unchanged.\n- **Unresolved coverage gaps:**\n  - quantitative yields/selectivities are mostly absent from the validated carried-forward artifact\n  - hydrothermal T/P/pH details are incomplete except for the preserved **200-275 \u00b0C** note\n  - no carried-forward direct clay-catalyzed de novo glycine synthesis row\n  - cyanosulfidic direct glycine production remains unresolved in the validated network\n  - iron-sulfur de novo synthesis remains contradicted by negative evidence\n\n## References\n\nAponte, J. C., et al. (2020). *ACS Earth and Space Chemistry*.\n\nAubrey, A. D., et al. (2009). *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*.\n\nAfrin, R., et al. (2018). *International Journal of Molecular Sciences*.\n\nAlonso, J. L., et al. (2018). *Astrophysical Journal*.\n\nBelloche, A., et al. (2008). *Astronomy & Astrophysics*.\n\nBernstein, M. P., Sandford, S. A., Allamandola, L. J., Chang, S., and Scharberg, M. A. (1995). *Astrophysical Journal*.\n\nBernstein, M. P., et al. (2002). *Nature*.\n\nBizzarri, B. M., et al. (2021). *International Journal of Molecular Sciences*.\n\nBl\u00f6chl, E., Keller, M., W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, G., and Stetter, K. O. (1992). *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences USA*.\n\nBujd\u00e1k, J., Eder, A., Yongyai, Y., Fayb\u00edkov\u00e1, K., and Rode, B. M. (1995). *Jou