onse": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.96,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.94\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.95,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.97,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.98,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.95,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the strongest and most coherent pathway in the network. It matches the validated literature very closely: formaldehyde + HCN + NH3 to aminoacetonitrile, followed by hydrolysis to glycine. The only mild issue is environmental labeling: the first step is presented as Surface whereas the literature frames it more generally as aqueous prebiotic solution rather than requiring a surface setting.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Refine rxn_001 environment from specifically Surface to a more general aqueous prebiotic setting unless a surface-specific justification is provided\",\n        \"Include explicit citation-level support in the reaction metadata if this were being re-issued as a formal network JSON\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.93\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.93,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.95,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.97,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"The one-pot Strecker net reaction is literature-supported by mechanistic work and is chemically reasonable as a net transformation. However, as a network step it compresses the aminonitrile intermediate and is less explicit than P1. Labeling it Biochemical is weaker than labeling it as general aqueous prebiotic chemistry.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent rxn_003 as an overall net reaction while preserving aminoacetonitrile as the mechanistic intermediate\",\n        \"Adjust the environment label from Biochemical to aqueous prebiotic or Surface/Bulk aqueous if the schema allows\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.94\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.94,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.95,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.97,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.94,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is well aligned with astrochemical Strecker-like precursor formation from methanimine, NH3, and HCN to aminoacetonitrile, followed by hydrolysis to glycine. It captures a key literature-supported alternative entry into the same aminonitrile hub.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Clarify that the first step is specifically an ice-matrix/astrochemical analog process rather than a generic terrestrial surface reaction\",\n        \"Indicate how aminoacetonitrile is transferred from an ice-analog context to a hydrolytic aqueous setting\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.83,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.94\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.79,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n      \"feedback\": \"The first step is broadly aligned with cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry accessing aldehydic precursors, but the representation is oversimplified because HCN does not cleanly become both glycolonitrile and formaldehyde in a single elementary reaction. The major weakness is rxn_007: the validated literature supports glycolonitrile + NH3 + H2O giving glycine-related or aminonitrile-accessible intermediates, not direct aminoacetonitrile formation with high confidence. This pathway is therefore only partially supported.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Split rxn_005 into better-defined photoredox precursor-generating steps\",\n        \"Downgrade rxn_007 to a looser precursor-space step unless direct experimental support for aminoacetonitrile is shown\",\n        \"Make the mechanistic transition from glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile explicit and literature-cited\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.94\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.8,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway captures the literature point that cyanosulfidic chemistry accesses alpha-aminonitrile precursor space including the glycine precursor. However, the network represents that support too strongly as direct production of aminoacetonitrile from only HCN and HS-. The literature emphasizes a broader UV/Cu photoredox network, not this compressed stoichiometric step.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_006\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Expand rxn_006 to include UV and Cu/cyanometallate photoredox system explicitly in the reaction definition\",\n        \"Phrase the output as precursor space including aminoacetonitrile rather than guaranteed direct formation\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.93\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.79,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.84,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.91,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.8,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway has reasonable convergence logic but is somewhat redundant and partly double-counts Strecker completion after already invoking a cyanosulfidic aminonitrile route. The weakest point remains the over-compressed cyanosulfidic step.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_006\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Simplify the sequence to avoid redundant glycine-forming closure steps\",\n        \"Use cyanosulfidic chemistry as feeder chemistry into Strecker precursors rather than as a direct aminonitrile-producing shortcut\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.97\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.96,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.95,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.98,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.96,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is one of the best-supported direct pathways in the validated literature. UV irradiation of H2O + CH3NH2 + CO2 ice analogs to glycine is explicitly supported. The only minor caveat is that this is best described as astrochemical ice photochemistry rather than a standard terrestrial surface pool environment.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Clarify that the environment is UV-irradiated ice film / astrochemical analog\",\n        \"Note the literature caveat that extended UV can also photodestroy glycine\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.91\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.89,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.94,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.9,\n      \"feedback\": \"The mixed-ice UV pathway is literature-supported in broad form, but the network specifies H2O, CO2, CH3NH2, and HCN as a defined input set whereas the carried-forward literature row is more generic about realistic ice mixtures. Still, glycine detection in irradiated mixed ice analogs is well supported.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Avoid over-specifying the exact mixture unless directly tied to a particular cited experiment\",\n        \"Separate this route from rxn_008 more clearly by distinguishing realistic mixed ices from minimal feedstock systems\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.92\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.91,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.95,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.94,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway aligns well with the validated hydrothermal vent simulation literature for ethanolamine to glycine. It is one of the better hydrothermal entries because it uses a specific feedstock and not an overgeneralized vent miracle step.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Include the metal-powder and alkaline vent-simulation detail explicitly in the reaction metadata\",\n        \"If available, connect ethanolamine provenance more explicitly to upstream chemistry\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.96\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.95,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.94,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.97,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.95,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is highly aligned with the validated 2024 mineral-mediated route from glyoxylate and nitrate on ferroan brucite to glycine. It is specific, direct, and well matched to the literature as summarized.\",\n      \"approv