 American Chemical Society*.\n\nOgata, Y., et al. (2000). *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*.\n\nPaecht-Horowitz, M. (1976). *Origins of Life*.\n\nPatel, B. H., et al. (2015). *Nature Chemistry*.\n\nPeltzer, E. T., Bada, J. L., Schlesinger, G., and Miller, S. L. (1984). *Advances in Space Research*.\n\nPoggiali, G., et al. (2020). *Frontiers in Astronomy and Space Sciences*.\n\nPulletikurti, S., et al. (2022). *Nature Chemistry*.\n\nRitson, D., and Sutherland, J. D. (2012). *Nature Chemistry*.\n\nRitson, D., and Sutherland, J. D. (2013). *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*.\n\nRotelli, L., et al. (2016). *Scientific Reports*.\n\nThrush, K. L., and Kua, J. (2018). *Journal of Physical Chemistry A*.\n\nXu, J., et al. (2018). *Chemical Communications*.\n\nYanagawa, H., Nishizawa, M., and Kojima, K. (1984). *Origins of Life*.\n\nZhang, X. V., et al. (2016). *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*.\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.87\n- Feedback: The network is strong in breadth, convergence, and literature coverage, and it clearly reaches the target glycine through multiple independently supported route families. Topologically it is well connected, with good hub usage centered on HCN, formaldehyde, aminoacetonitrile, glycine, and CO2. Convergence is clear at aminoacetonitrile and glycine. The strongest literature-aligned components are the classical Strecker route, astrochemical methanimine-to-aminoacetonitrile route, UV-ice glycine formation, ethanolamine hydrothermal conversion, and the ferroan-brucite glyoxylate+nitrate route. Major weaknesses are concentrated in the cyanosulfidic branch, where the network overstates directness from HCN/HS- to aminoacetonitrile and from glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile. There is also one notable literature-alignment issue in rxn_011: direct vent-like glycine from simple feedstocks is contested in the literature and should be represented cautiously. Another schema-level problem is that Hydrothermal and Surface reactions are described without explicit mineral agents, despite the synthesis-network instructions requiring them. Finally, the network includes downstream peptide formation plausibly, but rxn_013 is misclassified as Biochemical rather than iron-sulfur/hydrothermal surface chemistry, and rxn_014 compresses oligomerization in a way that is less specific than the supporting literature. Overall, this is a good but not approval-level network under the strict >=0.9 threshold because of incomplete mineral specification and some overstated cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n- Issues: ['The first step is broadly aligned with cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry accessing aldehydic precursors, but the representation is oversimplified because HCN does not cleanly become both glycolonitrile and formaldehyde in a single elementary reaction. The major weakness is rxn_007: the validated literature supports glycolonitrile + NH3 + H2O giving glycine-related or aminonitrile-accessible intermediates, not direct aminoacetonitrile formation with high confidence. This pathway is therefore only partially supported.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the abo