ility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.84,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.91,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is strongly literature supported at the route-family level because realistic UV-irradiated ice analog mixtures do produce glycine. The main weakness is network abstraction: the listed inputs are a simplified subset of what the literature describes as complex realistic mixed ices, so the reaction node is more representational than stoichiometrically explicit.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Annotate rxn_009 as a mixture-to-product route rather than an exact stoichiometric reaction.\",\n        \"Differentiate it more clearly from rxn_010 to avoid redundancy.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.86,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.95,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n      \"feedback\": \"Good hydrothermal pathway with direct support from the validated set for ethanolamine to glycine in alkaline vent simulations. It is less broadly established than Strecker or UV-ice chemistry and depends on specific hydrothermal simulation conditions, but it is a reasonable inclusion. The summary should have specified the metal powders/mineral agents explicitly.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add the reported alkaline hydrothermal vent simulation context and metal powder agent explicitly.\",\n        \"Clarify plausible source of ethanolamine within the larger network.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.93\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      