 American Chemical Society*.\n\nOgata, Y., et al. (2000). *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*.\n\nPaecht-Horowitz, M. (1976). *Origins of Life*.\n\nPatel, B. H., et al. (2015). *Nature Chemistry*.\n\nPeltzer, E. T., Bada, J. L., Schlesinger, G., and Miller, S. L. (1984). *Advances in Space Research*.\n\nPoggiali, G., et al. (2020). *Frontiers in Astronomy and Space Sciences*.\n\nPulletikurti, S., et al. (2022). *Nature Chemistry*.\n\nRitson, D., and Sutherland, J. D. (2012). *Nature Chemistry*.\n\nRitson, D., and Sutherland, J. D. (2013). *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*.\n\nRotelli, L., et al. (2016). *Scientific Reports*.\n\nThrush, K. L., and Kua, J. (2018). *Journal of Physical Chemistry A*.\n\nXu, J., et al. (2018). *Chemical Communications*.\n\nYanagawa, H., Nishizawa, M., and Kojima, K. (1984). *Origins of Life*.\n\nZhang, X. V., et al. (2016). *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*.\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.87\n- Feedback: The network is strong in breadth, convergence, and literature coverage, and it clearly reaches the target glycine through multiple independently supported route families. Topologically it is well connected, with good hub usage centered on HCN, formaldehyde, aminoacetonitrile, glycine, and CO2. Convergence is clear at aminoacetonitrile and glycine. The strongest literature-aligned components are the classical Strecker route, astrochemical methanimine-to-aminoacetonitrile route, UV-ice glycine formation, ethanolamine hydrothermal conversion, and the ferroan-brucite glyoxylate+nitrate route. Major weaknesses are concentrated in the cyanosulfidic branch, where the network overstates directness from HCN/HS- to aminoacetonitrile and from glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile. There is also one notable literature-alignment issue in rxn_011: direct vent-like glycine from simple feedstocks is contested in the literature and should be represented cautiously. Another schema-level problem is that Hydrothermal and Surface reactions are described without explicit mineral agents, despite the synthesis-network instructions requiring them. Finally, the network includes downstream peptide formation plausibly, but rxn_013 is misclassified as Biochemical rather than iron-sulfur/hydrothermal surface chemistry, and rxn_014 compresses oligomerization in a way that is less specific than the supporting literature. Overall, this is a good but not approval-level network under the strict >=0.9 threshold because of incomplete mineral specification and some overstated cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n- Issues: ['The first step is broadly aligned with cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry accessing aldehydic precursors, but the representation is oversimplified because HCN does not cleanly become both glycolonitrile and formaldehyde in a single elementary reaction. The major weakness is rxn_007: the validated literature supports glycolonitrile + NH3 + H2O giving glycine-related or aminonitrile-accessible intermediates, not direct aminoacetonitrile formation with high confidence. This pathway is therefore only partially supported.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.88\n- Feedback: This is a good and substantially literature-aligned glycine synthesis network with strong convergence on glycine through Strecker, UV-ice, hydrothermal ethanolamine, and ferroan-brucite routes. The target is clearly achieved multiple times, hub selection is sensible, and the network reflects the literature finding that aminoacetonitrile, HCN, formaldehyde, and CO2 are central precursor nodes. It also correctly treats iron-sulfur chemistry primarily as downstream activation/processing rather than the main de novo source, which is a major strength relative to the validated evidence base. However, the network falls short of approval at the >=0.9 threshold for several reasons: several reaction nodes are overcompressed or represent route families rather than chemically explicit steps; some pathways rely on precursor-pool logic rather than direct stoichiometric transformations; several surface and hydrothermal reactions omit the required mineral/agent specification; the glyoxylate and ethanolamine branches are weakly connected upstream; rxn_012 appears to encode contested hydrothermal production as a direct reaction without reflecting uncertainty; and rxn_014 is not a good match to the literature because Huber and Wachtershauser support glycine activation/peptide formation on (Ni,Fe)S with CO, not a simple glycine + CO -> diglycine stoichiometric condensation. Overall, the network is chemically and topologically solid but not fully schema-compliant and contains a few mechanistic oversimplifications.\n- Issues: ['This is one of the weaker pathways. The literature supports glycolonitrile as an upstream Strecker-adjacent intermediate and discusses glycine-related products or aminonitrile-accessible intermediates, but the submitted reaction appears to force glycolonitrile + NH3 + H2O directly into aminoacetonitrile without sufficient mechanistic clarity. The path is conceptually adjacent to validated chemistry but underdefined.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Glycine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network targets glycine through ten literature-grounded, convergent prebiotic routes centered on four major hubs: HCN, formaldehyde, aminoacetonitrile, and glycine, with CO2 as an additional cross-environment feedstock hub. The design follows the validated evidence base: classical Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis; astrochemical Strecker-like aminoacetonitrile formation from methanimine; cyanosulfidic photoredox access to aldehydic and aminonitrile precursor pools without overstating unsupported direct steps; direct UV-ice glycine formation from CH3NH2/CO2/H2O and from realistic ice mixtures; hydrothermal ethanolamine conversion under alkaline vent simulation; contested but retained vent-like glycine generation from simple hydrothermal feedstocks; and the mineral-mediated glyoxylate+nitrate+ferroan brucite route. Downstream reactions include iron-sulfur mediated peptide activation and hydrothermal oligomerization to connect synthesis to biochemical emergence. Negative FeS/H2S de novo evidence is explicitly included as a cautionary, non-productive hydrothermal branch so the network reflects the literature contradiction rather than inventing an unsupported positive route.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3N\",\n      \"