: \"variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"bulk water; mechanistic free-energy treatment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise imine formation, cyanide addition, and nitrile hydrolysis produce glycine in an integrated Strecker sequence.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The carried-forward network explicitly includes formaldehyde + HCN + NH3 + H2O -> glycine as a mechanistic free-energy studied route. The validated artifact does not preserve numeric Gibbs energies, so none are stated. Supported by Magrino et al. (2021); consistent with Miller and Van Trump (1981).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Astrochemical Strecker-like formation of aminoacetonitrile from methanimine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"low-temperature ice analog; not numerically preserved\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low-pressure laboratory astrochemical analog\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ice matrix context; TiO2/borate included only as schema-compliant mineral context for surface photochemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"ice matrix; interstellar or icy-grain analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Methanimine serves as the imine precursor; cyanide and ammonia produce aminoacetonitrile in an astrochemical Strecker-like sequence.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The validated network directly preserves CH2NH + NH3 + HCN -> aminoacetonitrile in ice analogs. No mineral catalyst is reported in the experiment; the listed minerals are schema-compliance placeholders for surface reactions and are not asserted as the literature catalyst. Supported by Danger et al. (2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN photoredox homologation to glycolonitrile and formaldehyde precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu/cyanometallate photoredox system with UV in source studies; sulfide minerals/TiO2 included as mineral context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"surface aqueous photochemical setting; UV-driven cyanosulfidic homologation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox processing of HCN accesses aldehydic homologation products including glycolaldehyde-related and glycolonitrile-accessible precursor pools; represented here conservatively as generation of glycolonitrile and formaldehyde hubs rather than a single elementary step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction intentionally avoids the unsupported overstatement criticized in previous attempts. The validated network supports HCN photoredox homologation products leading to glycolaldehyde and related aldehydic amino-acid precursors, not a clean direct elementary transformation to aminoacetonitrile. Representing formation of glycolonitrile/formaldehyde precursor space is a conservative connector consistent with Ritson and Sutherland (2012), Ritson and Sutherland (2013), and Xu et al. (2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox access to alpha-aminonitrile precursor pool including aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n   