erefore both aminoacetonitrile and glycine are included as accessible outputs from the intermediate pool. Supported by Thrush and Kua (2018); also consistent with Ritson and Sutherland (2013) and Kua and Paradela (2020) for glycolonitrile relevance.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct UV-ice glycine synthesis from methylamine and carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ice-film conditions; not numerically preserved\",\n        \"pressure\": \"vacuum/astrochemical analog\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation in ice film; TiO2/borate included only as schema-compliant mineral context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"ice film under astrochemical analog irradiation; extended UV can also photodestroy glycine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV processing of mixed ice containing H2O, CH3NH2, and CO2 yields glycine directly in the irradiated ice matrix.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The carried-forward reaction table directly preserves H2O + CH3NH2 + CO2 + UV -> glycine in ice films. Mineral agents are not part of the reported experiment and are listed only to satisfy the required schema for surface reactions. Supported by Lee et al. (2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"UV irradiation of realistic interstellar/cometary ice mixtures to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ice-matrix astrochemical analog; not numerically preserved\",\n        \"pressure\": \"astrochemical analog\",\n        \"catalyst