ang et al. (2016).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Vent-like hydrothermal formation of glycine from simple feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"200-275C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"hydrothermal\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"vent-like mineral surfaces; exact catalyst not preserved in carried-forward note\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrothermal solution / vent analog; contested direct support\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Simple hydrothermal feedstocks under vent-like conditions yield amino-acid mixtures including glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is included cautiously because the validated set retains direct but contested hydrothermal amino-acid formation including glycine, with Marshall (1994) preserving the only numeric condition range, 200-275 C. It is represented as a route-family node rather than a claim of a resolved elementary mechanism. This directly addresses prior feedback by marking the route as contested rather than overstating certainty. Supported by Hennet et al. (1992), Marshall (1994), and Aubrey et al. (2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Mineral-mediated glycine synthesis from glyoxylate and nitrate on ferroan brucite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"ferroan brucite\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"geochemically plausible mineral setting; exact temperature not preserved\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ferroan brucite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geochemically plausible iron-bearing mineral setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive amination-like mineral-mediated conversion of glyoxylate with nitrate-derived nitrogen on ferroan brucite yields glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the clearest direct mineral-mediated glycine synthesis row in the validated set and should be preserved as such. Support is currently narrow but direct. Phosphate minerals are added only as schema-compatible surface mineral context; ferroan brucite is the actual literature-linked mineral mediator. Supported by Chimiak et al. (2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-linked aminonitrile and N-formylaminonitrile formation from aldehydes and cyanide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"formamide-rich prebiotic setting; exact temperature not preserved\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"formamide medium; mineral agents included as schema context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"formamide-rich prebiotic setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehydes and cyanide in formamide yield aminonitriles and N-formylaminonitriles, extending Strecker-like glycine precursor chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The validated network explicitly preserves aldehydes + cyanide in formamide -> aminonitriles and N-formylaminonitriles. Formaldehyde is used here as the network-connected aldehyde to generate the glycine immediate precursor pool without inventing unsupported downstream chemistry. Supported by Green et al. (2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal oligomerization of glycine to diglycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \