\"environmental_progression\": 0.91,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.97,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.95,\n      \"feedback\": \"Best-supported direct glycine-producing pathway in the literature set. Direct UV-ice synthesis from H2O, methylamine, and CO2 aligns very well with Lee et al. The environmental framing is strong, although in the strict network schema the reaction is labeled Surface without a mineral agent, while the literature actually emphasizes an ice-film matrix rather than mineral catalysis.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"If maintaining a Surface label, note that the key agent is an ice matrix and UV irradiation rather than a mineral catalyst.\",\n        \"Mention photodestruction competition under extended UV exposure.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.93\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"Strong direct route based on realistic ice mixtures and UV irradiation, consistent with Bernstein, Mu\u00f1oz Caro, and related astrochemical literature. Slight deduction because the reactant list is more specific than the validated row, which refers to mixed ice analogs rather than a fully resolved stoichiometric recipe.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Treat rxn_009 as a mixture-to-product transformation rather than a fixed stoichiometric reaction if maximum fidelity is desired.\",\n        \"Differentiate it from rxn_008 by emphasizing realistic complex ice composition.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.91\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.89,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.94,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.91,\n      \"feedback\": \"Good hydrothermal pathway with direct literature support from alkaline vent simulation work. Main issue is schema compliance: hydrothermal reactions should specify mineral agents, and the literature preserves only 'metal powders' rather than one of the required mineral catalysts. Still, as a literature-aligned glycine route it is strong.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"State the hydrothermal condition more explicitly as alkaline vent simulation and, if possible, distinguish metal powders from mineral catalysts.\",\n        \"Avoid implying stronger catalyst specificity than the literature preserves.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.96\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.95,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.92,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.97,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.95,\n      \"feedback\": \"Excellent mineral-mediated direct route. Glyoxylate plus nitrate on ferroan brucite to glycine is one of the clearest direct mineral-supported routes in the validated set and is represented faithfully here.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Make ferroan brucite explicit as the agent in the reaction metadata if not already encoded.\",\n        \"Acknowledge that support is currently narrow but high quality.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a strong, well-connected glycine synthesis network with excellent literature coverage and clear convergence on the target from multiple route families. Topology is good: 21 molecules and 17 reactions exceed the minimum scale, the network is connected, and major hubs such as HCN, formaldehyde, aminoacetonitrile, glycine, and CO2 are appropriately reused across pathways. Convergence is a major strength, especially at aminoacetonitrile and glycine. Literature alignment is also strong overall: the network correctly prioritizes Strecker chemistry, UV-ice synthesis, astrochemical aminoacetonitrile formation, the alkaline hydrothermal ethanolamine route, the ferroan-brucite route, and the negative FeS/H2S de novo result. The explicit inclusion of a negative hydrothermal iron-sulfur branch is a notable strength because it reflects the contradiction in the source base rather than forcing an unsupported productive path. Main weaknesses are schema and reaction-specific fidelity issues. Several Surface and Hydrothermal reactions do not appear to specify mineral agents despite this being required. The cyanosulfidic branch is somewhat overstated in directness, especially for rxn_006 and rxn_007, where the literature supports precursor-space access more strongly than clean glycine production. Some environments are also assigned broadly; several reactions are better described as aqueous prebiotic, ice-analog, or formamide-medium processes rather than strictly Surface or Biochemical. Final target achievement is excellent because glycine is produced by multiple independent, literature-supported routes, and downstream conversion to diglycine/glycinamide further supports biochemical relevance. However, because of the missing catalyst metadata and a few overcompressed speculative steps, the network does not meet the very high approval threshold of 0.9 overall confidence.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.91,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.94\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.93, "rxn_002": 0.92}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.93, "pathway_coherence": 0.96, "environmental_progression": 0.88, "target_achievement": 0.97, "